1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:05,901
You're listening to: Building Healthcare Technology at Dr. Dangs Lab: What They Don't Teach You.

2
00:00:05,901 --> 00:00:13,353
3 years of building lab management systems taught me that healthcare software is nothing like regular SaaS.

3
00:00:13,353 --> 00:00:16,790
Here's what actually matters when patient care depends on your code.

4
00:00:16,790 --> 00:00:17,836
Let's get started.

5
00:00:17,836 --> 00:00:20,997
Now, let's talk about My First Week Was a Reality Check.

6
00:00:20,997 --> 00:00:24,543
I joined Dr. Dangs Lab thinking I knew how to build software.

7
00:00:24,543 --> 00:00:28,125
I'd worked on e-commerce, fintech, the usual stuff.

8
00:00:28,125 --> 00:00:30,228
Healthcare would be just another domain, right?

9
00:00:30,228 --> 00:00:33,870
On my third day, a doctor called our support line furious.

10
00:00:33,870 --> 00:00:40,588
A patient's critical test result was delayed by 4 hours because our notification system silently failed.

11
00:00:40,588 --> 00:00:44,543
The patient had a serious condition that needed immediate attention.

12
00:00:44,543 --> 00:00:46,418
Nobody was hurt, thankfully.

13
00:00:46,418 --> 00:00:48,786
But I went home that night and couldn't sleep.

14
00:00:48,786 --> 00:00:52,656
In my previous jobs, a bug meant someone's shopping cart didn't work.

15
00:00:52,656 --> 00:00:54,975
Here, it could mean something much worse.

16
00:00:54,975 --> 00:00:59,002
That's when I understood: healthcare software isn't about features.

17
00:00:59,002 --> 00:01:05,180
It's about reliability, accuracy, and the weight of responsibility that comes with every line of code.

18
00:01:05,180 --> 00:01:06,875
Moving on to What We Were Dealing With.

19
00:01:06,875 --> 00:01:10,877
Dr. Dangs Lab is one of India's leading pathology centers.

20
00:01:10,877 --> 00:01:13,377
When I arrived, the situation was:

21
00:01:13,377 --> 00:01:18,822
15+ collection centers across Delhi NCR sending samples to central labs.

22
00:01:18,822 --> 00:01:23,341
Thousands of patients daily expecting accurate, timely reports.

23
00:01:23,341 --> 00:01:27,439
80+ doctors and lab technicians depending on our systems.

24
00:01:27,439 --> 00:01:30,528
Legacy software that crashed during peak hours.

25
00:01:30,528 --> 00:01:35,504
Paper-based workflows causing 2-3 hour delays in report delivery.

26
00:01:35,504 --> 00:01:40,444
No real-time tracking - patients calling repeatedly asking "where's my report?".

27
00:01:40,444 --> 00:01:44,338
The previous system was a PHP monolith from 2010.

28
00:01:44,338 --> 00:01:45,576
It worked... mostly.

29
00:01:45,576 --> 00:01:48,581
But as patient volume grew, it started buckling.

30
00:01:48,581 --> 00:01:49,807
Reports got delayed.

31
00:01:49,807 --> 00:01:51,069
Data got lost.

32
00:01:51,069 --> 00:01:52,439
Staff were frustrated.

33
00:01:52,439 --> 00:01:55,504
My job: rebuild it without breaking anything.

34
00:01:55,504 --> 00:01:59,879
Next up: The Architecture We Built (After 3 Rewrites).

35
00:01:59,879 --> 00:02:02,475
I'm not going to pretend we got it right the first time.

36
00:02:02,475 --> 00:02:08,413
The current system is version 3, and each previous version taught us something painful.

37
00:02:08,413 --> 00:02:10,228
Why These Specific Choices.

38
00:02:10,228 --> 00:02:14,699
FastAPI for most services: Our team knew Python well.

39
00:02:14,699 --> 00:02:18,834
Healthcare has complex business logic that changes frequently.

40
00:02:18,834 --> 00:02:21,406
We needed to move fast on new features.

41
00:02:21,406 --> 00:02:26,165
The auto-generated API docs saved hours of documentation work.

42
00:02:26,165 --> 00:02:31,694
Go for report processing: Generating 500 PDFs simultaneously in Python?

43
00:02:31,694 --> 00:02:32,548
Forget it.

44
00:02:32,548 --> 00:02:37,103
Memory usage was unpredictable with Python's PDF libraries.

45
00:02:37,103 --> 00:02:42,560
Go gave us 15x performance improvement (I wrote about this in my microservices article).

46
00:02:42,560 --> 00:02:50,060
PostgreSQL, not MySQL or MongoDB: ACID compliance isn't optional when dealing with medical data.

47
00:02:50,060 --> 00:02:56,033
The JSONB columns let us handle semi-structured lab results without schema migrations every week.

48
00:02:56,033 --> 00:03:00,108
Row-level security for multi-tenant data isolation.

49
00:03:00,108 --> 00:03:05,060
Redis for more than just caching: Real-time sample tracking (pub/sub).

50
00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:08,509
Rate limiting (patients refreshing "where's my report?"

51
00:03:08,509 --> 00:03:09,699
50 times).

52
00:03:09,699 --> 00:03:12,295
Session management with automatic expiry.

53
00:03:12,295 --> 00:03:14,591
Task queues for async processing.

54
00:03:14,591 --> 00:03:17,307
Let's explore The Hardest Problems We Solved.

55
00:03:17,307 --> 00:03:21,213
Problem 1: Sample Tracking Without Losing Anything.

56
00:03:21,213 --> 00:03:25,997
A sample travels through multiple hands: Collected at a center.

57
00:03:25,997 --> 00:03:28,473
Transported to lab (could take hours).

58
00:03:28,473 --> 00:03:29,663
Received at lab.

59
00:03:29,663 --> 00:03:30,625
Processed.

60
00:03:30,625 --> 00:03:31,947
Results entered.

61
00:03:31,947 --> 00:03:33,257
Report generated.

62
00:03:33,257 --> 00:03:34,759
Delivered to patient.

63
00:03:34,759 --> 00:03:39,326
If ANY step fails silently, someone's diagnosis gets delayed.

64
00:03:39,326 --> 00:03:42,451
Problem 2: Report Generation at Scale.

65
00:03:42,451 --> 00:03:47,668
On busy days, we generate 3,000+ reports.

66
00:03:47,668 --> 00:03:52,331
Each report is a multi-page PDF with: Patient demographics.

67
00:03:52,331 --> 00:03:54,627
Test results with reference ranges.

68
00:03:54,627 --> 00:03:56,262
Interpretation notes.

69
00:03:56,262 --> 00:03:58,149
Doctor's signature (digital).

70
00:03:58,149 --> 00:04:00,396
QR code for verification.

71
00:04:00,396 --> 00:04:05,685
Our first approach (synchronous, one-by-one) took 6 hours on peak days.

72
00:04:05,685 --> 00:04:07,271
Patients were furious.

73
00:04:07,271 --> 00:04:10,132
Problem 3: The "Where's My Report?"

74
00:04:10,132 --> 00:04:10,889
Problem.

75
00:04:10,889 --> 00:04:15,060
Patients would call 10-20 times asking for their report status.

76
00:04:15,060 --> 00:04:17,355
Our support team was overwhelmed.

77
00:04:17,355 --> 00:04:19,230
We built real-time tracking:

78
00:04:19,230 --> 00:04:22,704
Now let's look at Healthcare-Specific Lessons (The Hard Way).

79
00:04:22,704 --> 00:04:24,411
1. Audit Everything.

80
00:04:24,411 --> 00:04:25,913
No, Really, Everything..

81
00:04:25,913 --> 00:04:29,230
2. Lab Equipment Integration is a Nightmare.

82
00:04:29,186 --> 00:04:34,508
Modern analyzers speak HL7 (a healthcare data format from the 1980s).

83
00:04:34,508 --> 00:04:36,876
Parsing it is... an experience.

84
00:04:36,876 --> 00:04:39,640
3. Downtime is Not an Option.

85
00:04:39,640 --> 00:04:42,212
Now, let's talk about The Results After 2 Years.

86
00:04:42,212 --> 00:04:44,172
What Changed, Before, After.

87
00:04:44,172 --> 00:04:51,095
Report delivery time, 24-48 hours, 4-6 hours (90% under 2 hrs).

88
00:04:51,095 --> 00:04:54,087
Daily support calls, 200+, ~30.

89
00:04:54,087 --> 00:04:58,859
System downtime/month, 4-5 hours, <5 minutes.

90
00:04:58,859 --> 00:05:03,907
Data entry errors, ~5%, <0.5%.

91
00:05:03,907 --> 00:05:08,511
Patient satisfaction score, No data, 4.6/5.

92
00:05:08,511 --> 00:05:15,926
But the number I'm most proud of: zero data breaches, zero lost samples, zero incorrect reports in production.

93
00:05:15,926 --> 00:05:18,042
Moving on to What I Wish Someone Had Told Me.

94
00:05:18,042 --> 00:05:20,938
Healthcare moves slowly for good reasons.

95
00:05:20,938 --> 00:05:25,662
Doctors and lab techs have workflows burned into muscle memory.

96
00:05:25,662 --> 00:05:27,417
Change needs to be gradual..

97
00:05:27,417 --> 00:05:30,566
Regulations aren't obstacles, they're guardrails.

98
00:05:30,566 --> 00:05:36,119
HIPAA-like requirements forced us to build better systems than we would have otherwise..

99
00:05:36,119 --> 00:05:37,585
Paper isn't going away.

100
00:05:37,585 --> 00:05:40,145
Many doctors still want printed reports.

101
00:05:40,145 --> 00:05:42,020
Design for hybrid workflows..

102
00:05:42,020 --> 00:05:45,205
Every error message might be read by a panicking patient.

103
00:05:45,205 --> 00:05:48,571
"Report generation failed" causes anxiety.

104
00:05:48,571 --> 00:05:53,258
"Your report is being prepared and will be ready in 30 minutes" is better..

105
00:05:53,258 --> 00:05:55,698
The people using your software are exhausted.

106
00:05:55,698 --> 00:05:57,645
Lab techs work 10-hour shifts.

107
00:05:57,645 --> 00:05:59,160
Make the UI obvious.

108
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:00,422
Reduce clicks.

109
00:06:00,422 --> 00:06:01,684
Don't make them think..

110
00:06:01,684 --> 00:06:05,530
Building healthcare software changed how I think about engineering.

111
00:06:05,530 --> 00:06:08,342
Speed matters, but accuracy matters more.

112
00:06:08,342 --> 00:06:11,936
Features are nice, but reliability is essential.

113
00:06:11,936 --> 00:06:16,852
And at the end of the day, there's a patient waiting for results that might change their life.

114
00:06:16,852 --> 00:06:22,525
If you're considering healthcare tech, know that it's harder than regular SaaS - but also more meaningful.

115
00:06:22,525 --> 00:06:26,407
Every optimization you make helps real people get better care.

116
00:06:26,407 --> 00:06:28,282
Working on healthcare systems?

117
00:06:28,282 --> 00:06:30,398
I'd love to hear about your experiences.

118
00:06:30,398 --> 00:06:33,523
Connect on LinkedIn or check out my other technical articles.

